Same problem here!

I had to comment line `model_zoo_intel_object_detection.cpp` [96](https://github.com/openvinotoolkit/model_server/blob/main/src/custom_nodes/model_zoo_intel_object_detection/model_zoo_intel_object_detection.cpp#L64) and [309](https://github.com/openvinotoolkit/model_server/blob/main/src/custom_nodes/model_zoo_intel_object_detection/model_zoo_intel_object_detection.cpp#L309) because they were giving some weird errors in pipeline like: Model A has (0,1,3,256,256) shape with Model B (1,3,256,256). Even if i remove `demultiply_count`. 

In the end, the pipeline works for One Object, but if I have two or more it fails due to batch_size, with the original implementation I was no able to create the pipeline due to shape mismatch between nodes.

Hello @carlosmonteirobefore,
 
> I have a custom pipeline break when model_zoo_intel_object_detection crop two or more images to landmarks_regression_retail_0009, does anyone have ideas to solve this problem?

I assume that you will have variable number of object detected. In that case you have to use demultiplexer in order for this DAG to work. You need to add parameter to node that is extracting images `"demultiply_count": 0`.

Additionally you did set the parameter `"max_output_batch" = "1"` this have to be adjusted as well. Idea for this parameter in example custom node is to limit maximal number of detected objects. If for some reason unreasonable number of objects is detected then this will limit the impact of such cases.

Hello @pedromoraesh

Custom nodes that are extracting images are to be used with demultiplexer. They intentionally produce outputs with additional dimension that is later on stripped by demultiplexing.

> Model A has (0,1,3,256,256) shape with Model B (1,3,256,256)

If you are not using the demultiplexer then the first dimension will not be stripped. In cases when you always have the same number of objects detected you could rewrite the custom node to omit adding this additional dimension and then follow this up with model that is handling just that one batch size on input. However then you loose flexibility.

> If you can give me some explanation about those shards, just to understand better the error I would be appreciated.

This time the issue seems to be on our side. I have idea how the fix should look like. It seems that we do the validation of shards too soon before gathering (we do it when we setInput for the gathering node, while we should delay that check just before shards merging). This will occur if you have pipeline that:

NodeA(demultiplexer) -> demultiplexerOutput
-> demultiplexerOutput -> customNode
-> demultiplexerOutput -> modelNode

Good that you were able to workaround this issue on your own.

> @atobiszei Well Done Sir, the pipeline is AVAILABLE now and it works.
